Great food! Great portions. Reasonably priced. The only drawback is the lack of prompt and convenient service. My sister raved about the Pwason Gwo Sel I believed it was called and she's from a costal town in Haiti. My griyo was on point and the Banann Peze was just my level of crispy. On the service part, things were a bit more shaky. There can be a line and there's no easy way to order as far as I could tell. While it appeared like you could order on the phone, I'm not sure it actually starts your order. I think it's a check on whether they actually have what you want rather than a request to get your items ready for you to pay once you're there. Anyway, that's how I perceived it since they never asked for any sort of name or phone number and or a payment method. And since it doesn't seem to affect your waiting time by that much, I'm pretty convinced by now having gone through the same issues at other establishments. If you're looking for good haitian food and you don't mind a little less traditional service, it's enjoyable in it's quintessential haitian-ness.
